\begin_layout Section
Elasticity of demand and conspicuous consumption in middle-Africa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Africa is on track to observer rapid development in the coming decades -
 but the phenomenal growth prospects of African countries are not without
 the political risks faced by countries in South and South-East Asia.
 The proposed study aims to assess the recent growth of African countries
 (more particularly the countries : Kenya, Ethiopia) in relation to Asian
 countries - with respect to utility and demand elasticities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wider goal of the project is finding out spending patterns and the control
 over them exercised by societies.
 Despite the possibility of dramatic change, social attitudes are slow to
 detect and change at a differential pace
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "krosnick_attitudes"

\end_inset

.
 The study intends to measure this control as sensitivity to general trends
 across countries - in the hope to identify common consumption patterns
 across countries and account for differences in these trends.
 The study wishes to test whether trends such as gold consumption in India
 and sports expenditure in the U.S.
 can be evident from such an analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The study thus wishes to compare items of signaling effect vs consumption
 goods and among countries of similar economic output and consumption levels.
 This rather vast ambition is to be achieved by a conscious avoidance of
 a psychological analysis for the study.
 A sociological analysis as by Breckenridge (who classify consumption of
 goods (in India) in terms of pleasure, fantasy and style
