\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The association of spending patterns with social attitudes is thus of only
 secondary interest to the proposed study.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Focusing on product-pairs and advertising elasticities - the study wishes
 to find out if African demand differs from the rest of Asia and how well-equipp
ed the current state of market in Africa is to address these demands.
 I test whether with technology and increased access to information vis-a-vis
 the speed of reception of signals such as the role of spouses, elders etc.
 in consumer-decisions - can lead to assumptions of efficient markets in
 middle-Africa.
 The studies on advertising elasticity in middle-Africa are relied upon
 to measure market's adaptability.
 The study may thus be used to comment upon market failure for for the selected
 set of products in these countries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sensitivity of these items to economic goals is of importance to policy.
 I am driven by seemingly disparate goals of serving the investment community
 and studying history to understand the stability of the patterns of response
 to economic conditions.
 My contention is that adjustment and sustenance of these consumption patterns
 should allow us to gauge the economic feasibility of growth.
 Analysis of countries like Burma can be improved in this regard.
 The goal is to delve into economic history to see - why certain patterns
 have prevailed (gold consumption in India, sports in the US) and what it
 implies to policy measures.
 For understanding of economic history, I find the comparison with settler
 societies as key to our understanding of the problems of developing world.
 However, this comparison is of minor concern to this research and is rather
 beyond the scope defined.
\end_layout

